      Contract Number: 12825
      
      The Meadway shopping centre and housing estate is earmarked for demolition and the site is to be redevelopment, therefore identifies the need for safe demolition and site clearance. 
      
      The site must be well secured by use of appropriate fencing during and at the end of the contract.
      
      Contractors wishing to tender for this contract must have 3 years of audited accounts showing a minimum annual average turnover of Â£2.5 Million.
      The contractor must provide suitably trained workforce and experience/knowledge of works required to be undertaken. The contractor will be responsible for providing their own power, water and welfare to undertake this work.
      A Public/Product liability insurance of Â£5 million and Employers Liability Insurance of Â£10 million must be provided and the contractor must hold or employ persons with valid HSE asbestos license to be able to remove notifiable asbestos (if any).
      
      The contract will be let using a JCT Measured Term Form of Contract 2011 issued by the Joint Contracts Tribunal with Birmingham City Council amendments.

The successful contractor will need to demonstrate their ability to provide the service required, confirmation of conforming to demolition, asbestos and other relevant health and safety legislation, equalities, business charter and social value policy and financial stability.

column69: Integrated Community Anticoagulation Service - Croydon
column70:
NHS Croydon Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is inviting suitably qualified and experienced Providers of Anticoagulation Services to register their interest in this future opportunity. The purpose of this engagement is to inform the contracting approach for the future Integrated Community Anticoagulation service and to gauge the level of market interest.
The CCG is encouraging services to innovate to provide both non-complex and complex care out of hospital in a community setting. 
The overall aims of the Integrated Community Anticoagulation service will be to:
- Provide a cost effective, standardised, clinically effective and safe Integrated Community Anticoagulation service;
 - Improve quality and clinical outcomes through standardisation of care across an integrated pathway;
 - Enable patients to have equitable access to a range of medications and treatments in a convenient community or domiciliary setting;
 - Provide comprehensive and ongoing education to support medication adherence and patient self-management

The duration of the contract will likely be for 3 years with the option to extend for up to a further 2 years at the CCGs discretion. The CCG intends for the service to commence in April 2018. The indicative annual contract value for this service is approximately Â£1,300,000.

Additional information: ***Bidders interested in providing this future are asked to confirm this by email to ekkehard_kugler@nhs.net by 4th August 2017.  ***Your response is important, as the CCG reserves the right to use responses, or lack of them, to inform selection of the most suitable procurement process.
You are invited to CONFIRM YOUR INTEREST and engage with the CCG by reviewing the attached Draft Service Specification and explanatory Memorandum of Information (MOI), then ***COMPLETE & RETURN the attached Questionnaire via email to:

column69: Family Support Service
column70:
The London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham invite suitable expressions of interest and tenders for appointment to the Family Support Services Framework to deliver vital universal and targeted services to children aged 0-18 years. 

The establishment of a Family Support Service presents a unique opportunity to deliver a collaborative and community-focused service providing proactive, integrated, innovative and preventative support to families most in need. Hammersmith and Fulham Council welcomes interest from suppliers who will embrace this approach to the positive delivery of services which deliver positive outcomes for children, young people and their families living in Hammersmith and Fulham.

The Family Support Services Framework incorporates the following services:  

Lot number   Description
1.                    0-18 (0-25 if SEND) Central Locality service and the delivery of Borough wide evidence based parenting programmes
2.                   Children's Centre delivery (delivered in College Park and Old Oak, and Wormholt and White City wards)
3.                   Youth provision for young people with disabilities
4.                    Evidence based parenting and family support programmes
5.                    Mentoring for young people with targeted needs
6.                    Group based provision focused on specific local young people's targeted needs
7.                    Support for young people at risk of worklessness and adults out of work or at risk of financial exclusion
8                     Universal group based 0-18 years (0-25 if SEND) provision
9.                    Database management information
10.                  Tracking and Survey Activities Relating to Young People's Participation in Employment, Education, or Training

The Family Support Services Framework will be four years in duration commencing December 2017.  

Please note the contracts from this Framework will novate to a Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV), therefore all call off contracts will be contract managed by the SPV and future services will be called off by the SPV.  Further information is available in the tender document pack and attachments on this page from the recent market engagement event.

The evaluation criteria to be applied to this tender:
Compliance:           Pass/Fail 
Technical:              70%
Commercial:          30%

Deadlines
The deadline for returning your Tender is: 05:00:00 on Monday, 21 August 2017
Late applications will not be accepted.

Additional information: 
Please see opportunity at www.capitalesourcing.com

column69: NHS Scarborough & Ryedale CCG Integrated Prevention Community Care and Support Service PQQ
column70:
NHS Scarborough & Ryedale CCG is commissioning a partially integrated multi-speciality community provider model for the delivery of a range of community based health and care services (see II.2.4) for its registered and non-registered service users. The services include community services which are currently provided by a third party and some in-house CCG functions. It does not include primary medical care services. This is a 5 + 2 year contract which is subject to an affordability cap.  Contract will be the NHS Accountable Care Model Contract. 

Financial payment package is based on: Whole Population Payment; Improvement Payment Scheme; Gain/ Loss share; & KPI performance. Integration agreements with CCG's GP practices & local social care provider are required.

The CCG would like to receive innovative bids which meet the CCG's desire for a new model of service delivery. A range of first phase services will be required from the Service Commencement Date with second phase services deliverable from Year 2.

This service is being commissioned in respect of the relevant patient population of NHS Scarborough & Ryedale Clinical Commissioning Group. The locality encompasses the population of 15 GP practices.

Phase 1 services (from 3rd April 2018):
- Community Services (Ryedale) (including therapies)
- Community Services (Scarborough) (including therapies)
- Community Specialist Nursing
- Early Supported Discharge for stroke
- Community Response Team (Ryedale Hub)
- Community Response Team extension to Scarborough
Phase 2 services (from 1st April 2019):
- Elderly medicine outpatient services
- Primary care frailty service
- Continuing Healthcare assessment (including Funded Nursing Care)
- Fast Track care packages
Stated value is 7 year maximum - an affordability cap. All costs, liabilities including tax and profit elements must
come within this affordability cap.  The affordability cap contains an indicative budget for the Phase 2 services (April 2019) which is based on a series of assumptions made by the CCG. The CCG will be reviewing these assumptions and indicative budgets during Year 1 and will notify the Successful Bidder of any adjustments to the available budget for the Phase 2 services.

Execution of the service is reserved to a particular profession Reference to the relevant law, regulation or administrative provision:
Bidders should note that the services required are such that the Bidders will need to comply with the legal requirements for regulatory registrations both for the provider and individual staff members, for example:
- CQC registration;
- NHS Provider Licence (where applicable);
- individual professional registration requirements (e.g. GMC registrations).

Further details are available in the tender documents and specified in the Contract. Bidders should note that some registration applications have significant lead times and Bidders should make their own enquiries as appropriate.

Additional information: 
Interested providers requiring access to the PQQ and other relevant documents should email Beth Nixon on beth.nixon@brownejacobson.com to request access links to www.bjaccess.net which is the procurement portal for this Procurement Exercise.

This procurement falls under the "light touch" regime of Regulations 74 to 78 of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015. Therefore this procurement exercise is being run in accordance with the 2015 Regulations as they apply to "light touch" services.

The Integrated Support and Assurance Process applies to this procurement and the CCG reserves the right to take such steps as necessary to comply with this. NHS Scarborough & Ryedale CCG is part of the Capped Expenditure Process (see below) and reserves the right to take such steps as necessary to address and respond to this process.

The CCG reserves the right to:
- conduct engagement and consultation exercises where required to do so based on the solutions put forward by bidders to comply with legal obligations or as otherwise deemed necessary by the CCG
- move to a managed negotiation in the event it only receives 1 compliant response to its PQQ or if bidders drop out or are removed from the process leaving only 1 bidder
- amend, add to, or withdraw all, or any part, of any tender document, cancel this procurement at any time and consider alternative procurement options without any liability to operators, prospective bidders or bidders
- vary, at its discretion any published timetable in relation to the Procurement Exercise.

Across the local health system there are significant financial pressures. As a result, it has not been possible to produce financial plans that meet the funding allocations for York and Scarborough. This has caused the local health community to be placed into a process known as the Capped Expenditure Process (CEP), a national programme that includes a number of other financially challenged health communities. Further detail is contained in the PQQ.

NHS Scarborough & Ryedale CCG is working together, with NHS England and NHS Improvement, to draw up short-term financial recovery plans to improve the local financial position. At the same time, it is continuing to plan for the medium and longer term, focusing on designing better, more joined up services that will help people to stay well and reduce reliance on hospital-based care.

Bidders must submit a PQQ response. The PQQ sets out the rules of the Procurement Exercise, selection criteria & minimum requirements for selecting top 3 bidders for dialogue phase. There will be 1 round of dialogue.

Top 3 scoring bidders will be those who:
- pass all pass/fail questions;
- achieve a score greater than '0' on all scored questions (except finance);
- achieve an overall score of not less than 60%;
and are not otherwise excluded.
There is no minimum financial standing requirements but financial and economic standing is evaluated on a scored basis.

Healthwatch Staffordshire is an independent consumer champion for both health and social care services in Staffordshire. The aim of this service is to ensure they work in the best interests of patients, service users and residents and utilise intelligence gathered to influence commissioning and improve overall quality of health and social care provision.  
Staffordshire County Council will be going to market to recommission this service with effect from 1 April 2018. We want to commission a provider who can support and shape the Staffordshire Sustainability and Transformation Programme (STP) and the Health and Wellbeing Board priorities by ensuring plans reflect the patient and user voice. In doing this their role is to work with partners to improve the overall quality of health and care outcomes across Staffordshire. 
For the avoidance of doubt this service excludes the geographic area covered by Stoke-on-Trent City Council.
The successful provider will be expected to:
â¢	Have a good understanding of the Staffordshire's health and care system and develop effective working relationships with all key stakeholders in this area 
â¢	Provide support and influence key stakeholders in the design and delivery of Staffordshire's health and care priorities. 
â¢	Ensuring there is a public voice on how services are planned, commissioned and delivered to make a difference locally.
â¢	Make appropriate linkages with key decision making structures, including its statutory role on the Health and Wellbeing Board and supporting the Scrutiny Committee in their work programme to do this.
â¢	Have a good understanding of existing networks and utilise these as appropriate to deliver Healthwatch statutory functions.     
â¢	Ensure close working links with Staffordshire County Council's advocacy provider(s), in helping people to make a complaint about a local health service independent of the NHS.

column70:
The Student Recruitment CRM project workstream aims to deliver the software solution that will aid full engagement with these prospective students while aligning with new processes and ways of working for our colleagues supporting student recruitment across the University.

Operations 
The University supports enquiries from students from across the world for its programme offerings. Our earliest engagement with potential students can begin as early as initial senior school years through our outreach work, with full recruitment support through all stages through to registration and enrolment. We actively engage and support prospective international students with our overseas activities, directly or through third party agents.

Whilst very successful with student recruitment to date, we are continuously looking to improve our engagement and support, always aiming to provide the best student experience from their first contact with us. We in addition continue to review our ways of working to find more effective and efficient methods, enhancing the service we provide through utilising accessible software solutions 

Systems
Whilst without a CRM solution for student recruitment at present, we do fully utilise Tribal SITS to support application management and plan to continue to do so. The solution procured through this opportunity will need to be fully linked to the Tribal SITS installation and provide a means to connect with other systems also, potentially utilising an integration layer.

We are looking for a system to support us in the following areas, with Enquiry management a primary focus.
o	Enquiry Management. Enquiries capture (from Home/EU and International prospective students relating to UG, PGT (Post Graduate Taught) and PGR (Post Graduate Research programmes), processing and oversight/workflow

column69: Improving Access to Psychological Therapies - Croydon
column70:
NHS Croydon CCG is commissioning an Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) Service.

The CCG wishes to commission an IAPT service for Croydon residents ensuring a safe, high quality and innovative service provision across the London Borough of Croydon, in line with the CCG's strategic vision.  

The Croydon vision for an integrated IAPT service is one where all sections of the community are equally able to access the service; this will include communities which may be described as hard to reach. The service will maximise and ensure strong and effective links with physical health services to support people with, for example, long term conditions and medically unexplained symptoms where talking therapy may support better health outcomes. This will include links with pain management services to create a whole care pathway.
The CCG is looking for a single integrated service contract for the whole of the requirement.  In light of the CCG's knowledge of and engagement with current providers and the wider market, it is recognised that this may be delivered through an alliance based model with a lead provider working alongside smaller, more specialised service providers, particularly where patient and stakeholder engagement has often identified a preference for non-statutory providers including from BAME communities.
The service model should be innovative and developed with regard to increasing access rates beyond the minimum specified by the CCG for each year of the contract using the provider's expertise in delivering waiting times and recovery rates within the service model, but within the constraints of the financial envelope available for each year of the contract.

Improving access to psychological therapies is a national programme to increase the availability of 'talking therapies' on the NHS.

IAPT is primarily for people who have mild to moderate mental health difficulties, such as depression, anxiety, phobias and post-traumatic stress disorder. These conditions are treated using a variety of therapeutic techniques, including cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT), interpersonal therapy (IPT) and couples therapy. 

IAPT seeks to use the least intrusive method of care possible to treat people. This is often called a 'stepped care model' and means that the patient is generally offered a low intensity therapy in the first instance. This can include computerised CBT (cCBT) and guided self-help. If low intensity treatments are unsuccessful or inappropriate the patient will be 'stepped up' to high intensity. This often takes the form of one on one CBT.

The Croydon IAPT service is expected to increase the number of people accessing the service year on year in order that services move closer to compliance with the targets set out in the NSHE 5year Forward View, that by 2020/21 there will be increased access to psychological therapies so that at least 25% of people with common mental health conditions can access services each year.

Additional information: NHS Croydon Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is hosting a Bidder Briefing event for prospective bidders for the provision of IAPT services in Croydon.
The bidder briefing will provide interested organisations with an overview of the proposed new services and the CCGs requirements and desired outcomes. There will also be an overview of the procurement process and the opportunity to network with other providers.
The briefing will take place from 2pm on 25th July 2017. The briefing will be held at the following location:
Croydon Conference Centre, Surrey House, 5-9 Surrey St, Croydon CR0 1RG

column69: 9684 - Ground condition survey at Mile Cross Norwich
column70:
Mile Cross Business Centre is located on Mile Cross Road, Norwich, NR3 2DY  and is an asset of Norwich City Council's which up until very recently was used for a variety of different commercial purposes. This included but was not limited to City Works Depot, Copper recycling and wire stripping plant, vehicle repair, maintenance and servicing garage, canteen, radiator servicing, public gym and storage area for various other companies.
      It was also the location of the Norwich City Councils Property Services Office before being demolished in 2015. Previous commercial uses also include - A sawmill, blacksmiths and paint spraying company.
      Norwich City Council has started to look into the potential disposal or regeneration of the site, however, due to the continued change in its use over the years Norwich City Council needs absolute confirmation and guarantee that the site is "safe" for regeneration as detailed in Appendix L if either option is taken. Within the last 12 months, Norwich City Council commissioned a geotechnical site investigation / feasibility investigations into the potential disposal of or regeneration of the site. Please see Appendix L for details of the investigation, its findings and recommendations.
      An intrusive investigation report was commissioned with Harrisons Geotechnical Engineering Ltd. The report highlighted a number of hazardous vapours, contaminated soil, including asbestos from its previous and current uses. It is considered necessary to provide a more detailed investigation.
      Asbestos containing material throughout the site will need to be identified and clearly itemised by a suitably qualified individual before any potential commercial or residential development can be considered. 
      The full specification is detailed on Appendix J  contained in this advertisement.

column69: Learning Disability Market Day
column70:
To Providers and Voluntary Sector Organisations 

You are invited to take part in a Hammersmith and Fulham "Market Day" on the 14th September 2017 for people with learning disabilities over 16 years of age, their families, and carers, which is being co-produced with customers. 

The purpose of the day is to promote choice for customers, and to show case the types of activities and support which are available for people with learning disabilities in Hammersmith and Fulham, and which they could purchase with a personal budgets or direct payment.  

Day:    Thursday 14th September 2017 
Time:  1.00pm - 4.30pm 
            (light refreshments will be provided from 1pm onwards)
Place:  The Assembly Hall, Hammersmith Town Hall, King St, W6 9JU 

We would also like to encourage providers to come forward with offers to customers regarding managing personal budgets via Individual Service Fund arrangements. See link for more information. 

https://www.thinklocalactpersonal.org.uk/_assets/Resources/SDS/TLAPISFsContractingFINAL.pdf

In addition, we would also encourage provider organisations to attend who have personal budget, direct payment or Individual Service Fund offers for customers with high functioning autism or Asperger's Syndrome.   
 
Providers are encouraged to book a stall, market their services, and may also provide a "taster session" of an activity for customers and their families/carers to try out if they wish. 

Stalls are free for providers and voluntary sector organisations, who are encouraged to provide information leaflets outlining their services and/or activity offers for customers with personal budgets or direct payments.  

To book a stall or request more information please email David Goulding on David.Goulding@lbhf.gov.uk by the 11th August 2017 with the name of your organisation, contact details and a brief outline of the services you wish to market/show case on the day. 

Please ensure the information you plan to give out on your stalls is in easy read format.  See guidance in the attachments area below for more information .

If you wish to provide activity taster sessions, please say what they are so enough space can be provided. There are up to 18 stalls available which will be allocated on a first come first served basis, so please respond as early as possible 

An easy read leaflet to advertise this event for customers, carers and families will be available nearer the time.

Additional information: Providers please note:

â¢	This 'Market Day' event is part of preliminary market consultation to stimulate the provider market and promote choice for customers
â¢	This is not a call for competition.  For avoidance of doubt, this does not formally signify the beginning of a procurement exercise and does not constitute any commitment by the Councils to undertake any procurement exercise.
â¢	Participation in this event will not include or preclude any organisation from participating in any potential future formal procurement exercise 
â¢	Participation in this event by providers should not give rise to expectation that their organisation will have an agreement to make service offers to customers

column69: MINI TENDER FOR THE SUPPLY OF EDS AND EBSD SYSTEMS TO FIT ONTO A PLASMA-FIB/SEM
column70:
This is not a full OJEU process. The University has opted to publish this requirement for 15 - 20 days only , however, a full OJEU tender will not be undertaken.
      
      Specifications:
      
      1. An energy dispersive X-ray spectrometer (EDS) with large area (>60 mm2) silicon drift detectors (SDD) for chemical analysis is requested. The EDS system must be able to perform spot analysis, linescan and mapping, as well as be able to carry out peak identification and quantification functions in the software. It is highly desirable that the quantification function can be performed in spot analysis, linescan and mapping mode. Suppliers are requested to state the energy resolution (better than 129 eV) and the typical solid angle under specified typical operation conditions of the EDS system.

The tennis operator will be expected to deliver a fully inclusive community programme, comprising tennis activities for all ages and abilities as well as delivering to specific target groups identified by the local authority. column69: 14 095 Contract for the Design and Construction of A536 Congleton Link Road
column70:
The proposed A536 Congleton Link Road is a 5.7km long, 9.3m wide single carriageway road running to the north of Congleton between the A534 Sandbach Road in the west and the A536 Macclesfield Road in the northeast. The mainline has five 50m and one 60m diameter radii roundabouts including junctions with the A54 and A34. The link road passes beneath Chelford Road in an area subject to a high water table. The road will be cut approximately 8m deep into mudstone in a 25m high escarpment before crossing the River Dane on an 85m long bridge and landing on a 12m high embankment founded on piled alluvium. There are two other road bridge crossings and two underpasses. The scheme also has approximately 3.5km of realigned or new local roads and significant amounts of landscaping and environmental mitigation works to accommodate Great Crested Newts,Bats and Ancient Woodland.

Additional information: 
The Council wishes to appoint a suitable contractor to design & construct the works utilising the NEC3Engineering & Construction Contract Option A - Priced Contract with Activity Schedule.
The procurement process adopted by the Council is based upon the restricted tendering procedure as detailedin the Public Contracts Regulations 2015.
The restricted tendering procedure will be based upon two stages:
1.Selection Questionnaire (SQ) - Responses to the SQ will be evaluated taking into account the selectioncriteria set out in the SQ. Five suppliers will be short-listed to the Invitation to Tender stage.
2.Invitation to Tender (ITT) - The five short-listed suppliers will be invited to submit a tender based on ITTdocumentation. Responses to the ITT will be evaluated to determine the most economically advantageous tender,taking into account the award criteria set out in the ITT.

column68: RSSB2593 - T995-01 - Revise and refine current locomotive gauge in GERT8073 Appendix N
column69: RSSB2593 - T995-01 - Revise and refine current locomotive gauge in GERT8073 Appendix N  - Deadline Extended to July 21st
column70:
THE TENDER END DATE FOR THIS PROJECT HAS BEEN EXTENDED TO FRIDAY 21st July 5PM


This work package (WP1) is part of project T995 - Development of a new locomotive gauge, which includes two Work Packages: T995-01 Revise and refine current locomotive gauge in GERT8073 Appendix N  and T995-02 External Technical Expertise.
This project T995 - Development of a new locomotive gauge has two work packages:

â¢	Work Package 01- Revise and refine current locomotive gauge in GERT8073 Appendix N (described in this document)

â¢	Work Package 02 - External Technical Expertise

This project follows on from previous projects to develop standard vehicle gauges, namely T977 - Development of a revised lower sector vehicle gauge  and T978 Development of Passenger Standard Vehicle Gauges PG1 (20m) and PG2 (23m), which have already been delivered.  

This research workstream supports the Vehicle/ Structure System Interface Committee's (V/S SIC's) long term Gauging strategy which aims to:

a)	Maximise Capacity on Great Britain's Rail Network by adopting European size gauges/ vehicles over a core, nationwide network;

b)	Define and implement standard infrastructure and vehicle gauges and provide an optimised Customer experience at the Platform Train Interface;

c)	Lower Costs of gauging to the industry;

d)	Contribute to Great Britain's reduction in Carbon emissions through modal shift. 

This particular project (T995) looks at refining the current locomotive gauge so that it can be applied for both sides of the vehicle to infrastructure interface. The aim of the research is to have a matched loco/ infrastructure/ lower sector gauge family that will go 'nearly everywhere' with clear understanding and agreement of where a resultant compliant locomotive will not go and what the consequences/ costs/ benefits are of the resultant exception list of sites where the locomotive gauge has sub-standard clearance.

column69: Tender for the Supply and Installation of Particle Imaging Velocimetry Equipment
column70:
Tender for the Supply and Installation of Particle Imaging Velocimetry Equipment
      
      
      Three dimensional PIV system 
      o The device should be able to provide three dimensional velocity fields over both a thin plane of area 0.5m x 0.5m or over a measuring volume of at least 0.5m x 0.5m x 0.5m, with a sampling rate of at least 1000 samples / sec. Variations to this specification would be considered.
      o Velocities in the range of 0 to 40m/s, with an accuracy of 0.2m/s
      o The laser light source and optical system must be compliant with IEC 60825-1:2014
      o A suitable seeding system shall be provided that is appropriate to the TRAIN Rig conditions. 
      o A full data logging and processing system shall be provided, with the ability to download data to all common analysis platforms. 
      o The quote should include on site installation of the system at the TRAIN Rig
      o A training package must be provided for a group of users
      
      Support and service help 
      
      A reliable service package is required to ensure the full upkeep and efficiency of the product. This can range from service care contracts for durations after installation to warranties for equipment and what they include. This also will include all technical support and training as well as potential application requirements in the future. The suppliers will agree to provide operational support for the duration of the paid for service contract.

Additional information: www.in-tendhost.com/universityofbirmingham

column69: WCC - New Firefighter Basic Training - AWARD
column70:
Warwickshire County Council is seeking tenders for the provision of New Firefighter Basic Training for new recruits to its Warwickshire Fire and Rescue Service (WFRS).
      
      WFRS require a single supplier to deliver education of basic foundation knowledge & understanding of all core firefighter skills and associated foundation knowledge that will be established and delivered throughout a 12 week programme in the form of theory based lessons - trainees knowledge & understanding of the topic will tested throughout the training programme using a range of assessment methods.
      
      This specification is based on a 12 week residential course to be delivered in groups as described below:
      
      Group 1: 16 new recruits - Training to commence 4th September 2017 so that recruits are available for full-time duty at the beginning of December 2017.
      Group 2: Potentially a further 10 to 14 new recruits - Training to start in the 1st quarter of 2018 at dates to be agreed with WFRS to meet operational requirements.
      Group 3: Potentially up to 16 new recruits - Training to be carried out at dates to be agreed - expected to be in the second contract year.
      
      Please note that in respect of Groups 2 and 3 WFRS may elect to carry out some or all of the training in-house.
      
      
      These Services may be subject to modifications and changes in order to meet the changing needs and demands of the Council. This may also be as the result of additional (or reduced) funding streams.

column69: University of Sunderland - Furniture 2017 - AWARD
column70:
This opportunity is for NWUPC Framework FFE3050NW Contractors Only. 
      
      Only approved suppliers from the existing Framework will be attached to this Project.
      
      Expressions of interest outside the above framework will be rejected without further communication.
      
      The University have consistently been at the cutting edge of building redevelopment and refurbishments and have won a number of industry awards in recognition of our work within these areas.  A key element to both the design and operation of these successful building projects is the selection of appropriate furniture, fixtures and appropriate equipment.
      
      We are seeking to appoint a highly motivated and innovative supplier who will help shape and guide the furniture requirements of our highly vibrant and technology rich teaching and learning environments with a particular focus towards our new state of the art nursing facility based out of Shackleton House on City Campus.  The ability to provide agile, forward thinking and appropriate solutions will be key to the successful development of a partnership during the lifespan of this contract.  Although our primary core focus is teaching, the University also provide an excellent conferencing and banqueting provision which can be accessed by regional and national businesses; the successful supplier will need to demonstrate the ability to provide solutions aimed at this area in addition to standard teaching and learning spaces.
      
      As such, the University of Sunderland are seeking to appoint and engage with a single supplier from the North Western Universities Purchasing Consortium Framework Furniture (FFE3050NW) - Furniture to meet the following requirements covered under estimated and pipeline spend profile.
